{"id":"1809.09861","submitter":"Su Li","authors":"Su Li and Michael Gastpar","title":"Converse for Multi-Server Single-Message PIR with Side Information","comments":"17 pages, update","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"cs.IT math.IT","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Multi-server single-message private information retrieval is studied in the\npresence of side information. In this problem, $K$ independent messages are\nreplicatively stored at $N$ non-colluding servers. The user wants to privately\ndownload one message from the servers without revealing the index of the\nmessage to any of the servers, leveraging its $M$ side information messages. We\nassume that the servers only know the number of the side information messages\navailable at the user but not their indices. We prove a converse bound on the\nmaximum download rates, which coincides with the known achievability scheme\nproposed by Kadhe {\\it et. al.}. Hence, we characterize the capacity for this\nproblem, which is $(1+\\frac{1}{N}+\\frac{1}{N^2}+\\dots+\\frac{1}{N^{\\left\\lceil\n\\frac{K}{M+1}\\right\\rceil-1}})^{-1}$. The proof leverages a novel concept that\nwe call {\\it virtual side information}, which, for a fixed query and any\nmessage, identifies the side information that would be needed in order to\nrecover that message.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 26 Sep 2018 09:20:47 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Wed, 12 Jun 2019 15:06:57 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Fri, 1 Nov 2019 16:03:54 GMT"}],"update_date":"2019-11-04"}
